# pacman — arch / manjaro package manager primer
#
# pacman is one tool with single-letter operation flags. think of it as a state
# machine driven by a top-level mode:
#
#   -S   sync     (install / upgrade from a remote repo)
#   -R   remove   (uninstall)
#   -Q   query    (ask about already-installed packages)
#   -U   upgrade  (install a local .pkg.tar.zst file)
#   -D   database (mark packages as explicit/dependency, etc.)
#   -F   files    (search the file-list databases)
#   -T   test     (dependency checks)
#
# flags after the mode further specify behavior. e.g. -Ss searches the sync
# repos, -Qs searches installed. once you internalize the mode letters the
# rest reads naturally.
#
# pacman speaks to /etc/pacman.conf and /etc/pacman.d/mirrorlist. it does
# NOT talk to the AUR — that's what yay/paru are for (below).


SYNC / INSTALL / UPGRADE
------------------------

# refresh the package database (does not install anything)
sudo pacman -Sy

# upgrade EVERY package on the system (the standard maintenance command).
# always pair -Syu, never -Sy alone before installing — partial upgrades
# break arch installs in ways that are painful to recover from.
sudo pacman -Syu

# force-refresh the database even if it looks current (mirror weirdness)
sudo pacman -Syyu

# install one or more packages
sudo pacman -S firefox neovim

# install without prompting
sudo pacman -S --noconfirm firefox

# install but only download, don't actually install
sudo pacman -Sw firefox

# reinstall a package (useful for repairing corrupted files)
sudo pacman -S firefox

# install a local .pkg.tar.zst file (built by makepkg or downloaded)
sudo pacman -U ./mypackage-1.0-1-x86_64.pkg.tar.zst


REMOVE
------

# remove a package, leave its deps and its config files behind
sudo pacman -R firefox

# remove a package AND its no-longer-needed dependencies (the usual one)
sudo pacman -Rs firefox

# also wipe config files (-n = nosave)
sudo pacman -Rns firefox

# remove even if other packages depend on it (dangerous — breaks deps)
sudo pacman -Rdd firefox


QUERY (ask about installed packages)
------------------------------------

# list every installed package
pacman -Q

# count installed packages
pacman -Q | wc -l

# list only explicitly-installed packages (not pulled in as deps).
# this is your "what did I actually ask for" list — great for migration.
pacman -Qe

# list packages installed AS dependencies (would auto-remove with -Rs)
pacman -Qd

# list orphans: installed as dep but nothing depends on them now.
# safe to remove with: sudo pacman -Rns $(pacman -Qdtq)
pacman -Qdt

# info on an installed package (size, deps, install date, etc.)
pacman -Qi firefox

# list every file the package installed
pacman -Ql firefox

# show only the files marked as config files
pacman -Qii firefox | grep -i 'backup files' -A100

# which package owns this file? (arch equivalent of dpkg -S / rpm -qf)
pacman -Qo /usr/bin/firefox

# search installed packages by name+description
pacman -Qs python

# check installed package integrity (catches tampering, accidental deletion)
pacman -Qk firefox        # quick check
pacman -Qkk firefox       # full check (hashes, permissions, etc.)

# list packages NOT in any official repo (AUR, local builds, removed pkgs)
pacman -Qm


SEARCH SYNC REPOS (not yet installed)
-------------------------------------

# search for a package by name+description across enabled repos
pacman -Ss firefox

# info about a package in the repos (before installing)
pacman -Si firefox

# list every file a not-yet-installed package would put on disk.
# requires the files database — populate first with: sudo pacman -Fy
pacman -Fl firefox

# which package provides this file? (e.g. you ran a missing command)
sudo pacman -Fy            # refresh the files DB
pacman -F /usr/bin/strings


CACHE
-----

# package cache lives at /var/cache/pacman/pkg/
ls /var/cache/pacman/pkg/

# remove cached versions of installed packages (keeps current versions)
sudo pacman -Sc

# nuke the entire cache (free space; you lose downgrade rollbacks)
sudo pacman -Scc

# better: use paccache to keep the last N versions
sudo pacman -S pacman-contrib
paccache -rk2                          # keep 2 most recent of each
paccache -ruk0                         # purge cache for uninstalled pkgs


PACMAN.CONF / MIRRORS
---------------------

# main config
sudo vi /etc/pacman.conf

# enable the multilib repo (32-bit support — steam, wine)
# uncomment [multilib] and the Include line under it, then:
sudo pacman -Syu

# mirror list
sudo vi /etc/pacman.d/mirrorlist

# pick the fastest mirrors automatically
sudo pacman -S reflector
sudo reflector --country US --age 12 --sort rate --save /etc/pacman.d/mirrorlist


THE AUR (Arch User Repository)
------------------------------

# the AUR is community-maintained build recipes, not binaries. pacman does
# NOT talk to it directly — you need a helper or you build by hand with
# makepkg. don't run AUR helpers as root.

# install an AUR helper (one-time, from source)
sudo pacman -S --needed base-devel git
git clone https://aur.archlinux.org/yay.git
cd yay && makepkg -si

# yay (or paru) drives both pacman and the AUR with similar flags
yay -S google-chrome                   # install from AUR
yay -Syu                               # upgrade pacman repos AND AUR pkgs
yay -Ss spotify                        # search both repos and AUR
yay -Yc                                # clean orphaned AUR build files

# paru is a popular yay alternative (same flag surface), written in rust
sudo pacman -S --needed base-devel git
git clone https://aur.archlinux.org/paru.git
cd paru && makepkg -si


MANJARO SPECIFICS
-----------------

# manjaro IS arch underneath — pacman works exactly as above. differences:
#
# 1. manjaro ships its own holding repos. packages land in unstable first,
#    move to testing, then to stable on a delay (typically 1–2 weeks).
#    this is why `pacman -Syu` on a manjaro box can lag pure arch.
#
# 2. manjaro ships pamac as the front-end. it's a wrapper around pacman +
#    the AUR (you opt into AUR support in pamac's preferences).

# pamac CLI — flag surface differs from pacman, more verbose / apt-like
pamac update                           # = pacman -Syu
pamac install firefox                  # = pacman -S firefox
pamac remove firefox                   # = pacman -Rns firefox
pamac search firefox                   # searches repos + AUR if enabled
pamac info firefox
pamac list --installed
pamac list --orphans

# enable AUR support in pamac (off by default)
sudo vi /etc/pamac.conf                # uncomment EnableAUR
sudo systemctl enable --now pamac-daemon

# switch manjaro branches (stable → testing → unstable). more recent
# packages, more breakage. usually a bad idea on a daily driver.
sudo pacman-mirrors --api --set-branch testing
sudo pacman -Syyu

# manjaro's mirror picker (analogue of reflector on pure arch)
sudo pacman-mirrors --fasttrack 5 && sudo pacman -Syyu


PINNING / HOLDING A PACKAGE BACK
--------------------------------

# pacman has no real "apt-mark hold" equivalent — instead you blacklist
# the package in pacman.conf:
sudo vi /etc/pacman.conf
# add or extend: IgnorePkg = linux linux-headers nvidia
# then -Syu will skip those, prompting if there's an update available.


KEYRING / SIGNATURE TROUBLE
---------------------------

# if -Syu fails with "invalid or corrupted package (PGP signature)" after a
# long time without updating, the keyring is stale:
sudo pacman -Sy archlinux-keyring      # arch
sudo pacman -Sy manjaro-keyring        # manjaro
sudo pacman -Syu

# nuclear option — refresh and repopulate from scratch:
sudo pacman-key --init
sudo pacman-key --populate archlinux   # or: manjaro


WHAT TO CHECK AFTER A BIG UPGRADE
---------------------------------

# .pacnew / .pacsave files appear when pacman won't overwrite your edited
# configs. you need to merge them by hand or you'll keep running stale config.
sudo pacman -S pacman-contrib
sudo pacdiff                           # interactive 3-way diff merger
sudo find /etc -name '*.pacnew' -o -name '*.pacsave'

# what just got upgraded? pacman's log is the truth.
tail -50 /var/log/pacman.log
grep -E 'upgraded|installed|removed' /var/log/pacman.log | tail -30


COMMON DEV TOOLS
----------------

# the conventional bootstrap on a fresh arch / manjaro box. base-devel is a
# package GROUP (not a single package) — it pulls in gcc, make, autoconf,
# automake, pkgconf, patch, binutils, fakeroot, sudo, and the toolchain bits
# makepkg (and therefore every AUR helper) needs. --needed skips anything
# already installed, which matters because pacman otherwise reinstalls every
# member of the group.
sudo pacman -S --needed base-devel git

# see what's actually in a group before installing
pacman -Sg base-devel

# you can install a single member of a group too
sudo pacman -S gcc

# editors / shells
sudo pacman -S --needed neovim vim tmux zsh

# languages and runtimes — install only what you use
sudo pacman -S --needed python python-pip nodejs npm go rust clang cmake ninja

# debug / inspection
sudo pacman -S --needed gdb lldb strace ltrace valgrind

# containers / vms
sudo pacman -S --needed docker docker-compose qemu-full

# handy CLI
sudo pacman -S --needed ripgrep fd bat fzf jq htop wget curl unzip

# notes:
# - python on arch IS python 3 — no python2 in the repos.
# - PEP 668 means system pip is locked down. use venvs:
#       python -m venv .venv && source .venv/bin/activate
# - for rust, prefer rustup (pacman -S rustup; rustup default stable) over
#   the bare `rust` package if you need multiple toolchains.
# - IDEs and proprietary tools (vscode, jetbrains, chrome) usually live in
#   the AUR: `yay -S visual-studio-code-bin` once you have a helper set up.


